# Fluff Date: 2026-02-17 11:57:30
overview:<p>The Jackrabbit was developed in 2763 by Skobel MechWorks in response to a Star League Defense Force requirement for a light BattleMech capable of providing long-range fire support to infantry formations. The 25-ton design was intended to fill a niche between dedicated scout 'Mechs and heavier fire support platforms, offering autocannon-based firepower on a fast, maintainable chassis built with advanced Star League-era materials including an endo-steel frame and ferro-fibrous armor.</p><p>The Jackrabbit's timing proved spectacularly unfortunate. Approved for combat testing mere weeks before Stefan Amaris seized control of the Terran Hegemony, the entire production run of over five hundred units fell into Republican hands. The design became inextricably linked with the Amaris Empire, and despite the fundamental soundness of its chassis and subsystems, the Jackrabbit was shunned following the civil war. ComStar mothballed the surviving examples and the Skobel factory on Terra, where they remained in storage for nearly three centuries until the Word of Blake revived the production line during the Jihad.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Jackrabbit's design philosophy centered on providing infantry formations with organic long-range fire support, mounting an Armstrong JJ-Lite autocannon/2 as its primary weapon alongside a Holly Streak SRM-2 launcher for close-range engagements. Built on a Skobel 100-ROB endo-steel frame and protected by Krupp 150 ferro-fibrous armor, the design leverages advanced materials to maximize protection within its limited tonnage.</p><p>However, the Jackrabbit's armament proved to be its greatest liability. The class 2 autocannon, while offering respectable range, delivers negligible damage comparable to a machine gun burst, consuming precious tonnage that could have been allocated to a larger engine or additional armor. The GM 150 power plant provides adequate but unimpressive speed for a light 'Mech, reaching only 97 kilometers per hour, fast enough to keep pace with infantry but too slow to serve as a dedicated scout or to disengage from heavier opponents. The absence of jump jets further limits tactical flexibility, particularly in the urban environments where the design saw extensive combat during the Amaris Civil War.</p><p>Despite these shortcomings, technicians consistently praised the Jackrabbit's underlying engineering. The chassis proved remarkably reliable and easy to maintain, qualities that would later make it an attractive platform for ComStar's Nexus redesign program.</p>

deployment:<p>The original production model mounts the Armstrong JJ-Lite autocannon/2 and Holly Streak SRM-2 combination that defined the design's intended infantry support role. Armed with Star League-era technology including endo-steel construction and ferro-fibrous armor, the -8T represented a sound engineering platform hampered by inadequate weaponry. The bulk of the five hundred Jackrabbits produced for the Rim Worlds Republic were of this type, and the surviving examples inherited by ComStar remained in mothballed storage until the Word of Blake issued them to Protectorate Militia formations during the Jihad.</p>

history:<p>The Jackrabbit occupies a uniquely unfortunate position in BattleMech history. Developed from 2763 to meet a legitimate SLDF requirement for a light infantry support platform, the design was ready for production just as the Amaris Coup shattered the Star League in 2766. Skobel MechWorks' facilities on Terra fell to Republican forces, and Stefan Amaris ordered over five hundred Jackrabbits built to bolster his armies.</p><p>During the Amaris Civil War, the Jackrabbit's design flaws were brutally exposed. The light 'Mech lacked the speed to serve as an effective scout and carried insufficient firepower to threaten hardened targets, making it easy prey for SLDF forces. Running down Jackrabbits became something of a sport among SLDF MechWarriors, and the design suffered staggering combat losses exceeding eighty percent. None of the surviving machines were taken by General Kerensky's forces on Operation Exodus, cementing the Jackrabbit's status as a pariah design.</p><p>ComStar inherited both the surviving Jackrabbits and the Skobel factory on Terra following the fall of the Star League. Recognizing the taint attached to the design, ComStar placed them in deep storage, where they remained throughout the Succession Wars and into the Clan Invasion era. The few Jackrabbits deployed to Tukayyid in 3052 performed poorly against Clan forces, further reinforcing the design's negative reputation. Nevertheless, the Jackrabbit's dependable frame and ease of maintenance caught the attention of Precentor Martial Anastasius Focht, who in 3054 ordered the Skobel plant reactivated to produce the Nexus, a comprehensive redesign that would prove far more capable than its maligned ancestor.</p><p>Following the Word of Blake schism and their capture of Terra, the Blakists revived the original Jackrabbit production line alongside the Nexus and its successor designs. The Word of Blake established an auxiliary Skobel facility on Caph to supplement output and issued surviving Jackrabbits to their Protectorate Militia. The modernized JKR-9W variant entered production in 3074, representing the Word of Blake's effort to extract additional utility from the aging design. With the fall of the Word of Blake Protectorate, the remaining Jackrabbits passed to the Republic of the Sphere, though few remained in frontline service given the design's longstanding reputation.</p>

